Here is Docker architecture and its components, broken down clearly 👇

✅ Docker Client
↳ Sends commands to the Docker engine using the CLI.
↳ Communicates with the Docker Daemon via REST API.
↳ The interface between you and everything Docker does.

✅ Docker Daemon
↳ Builds, runs, and manages containers in the background.
↳ Handles images, containers, networks, and volumes.
↳ The actual engine doing the heavy lifting.

✅ Docker Host
↳ The machine where the Docker engine and containers operate.
↳ Could be your laptop, a VM, or a cloud server.
↳ Hosts everything Docker needs to run.

✅ Docker Registry
↳ Stores and distributes container images securely online.
↳ Docker Hub is the most common public registry.
↳ Private registries power enterprise deployments.

✅ Docker Images
↳ Read-only templates used to create containers quickly.
↳ Built using Dockerfiles, layered for efficiency.
↳ The blueprint for every container you spin up.

✅ Containers
↳ Lightweight, isolated environments running packaged applications consistently.
↳ Run identically across dev, staging, and production.
↳ The reason "it works on my machine" finally makes sense.

✅ Networks
↳ Enable communication between containers and external systems.
↳ Bridge, host, and overlay networks for different needs.
↳ The plumbing that connects services together.

✅ Volumes
↳ Persistent storage for container data beyond the container lifecycle.
↳ Survive container restarts and rebuilds.
↳ Critical for databases and stateful workloads.

✅ Docker Objects
↳ Images, Containers, Volumes, Networks.
↳ The four building blocks every Docker workflow revolves around.

The truth is - Docker commands are easy to memorise. Docker architecture is what separates people who use containers from people who design with them.

